</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFE2FFD06BC75B19FE74FE12" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFE2FFD06BC75B19FE74FE12" blockId="25.[192,1440,265,386]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06BC75B19FEB2FEB2" bold="true" box="[192,335,265,289]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of this species group can be defined by a unique combination of characters: vertex unarmed, apex of middle and hind femora truncate, scutellar scale lacking, and 
<collectionCode id="D6F2C089FFE2FFD06F7C5B3AFB70FED1" box="[1147,1165,298,322]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">T</collectionCode>
2 with only two integumental spots. Additionally, the genal carina is weak, the mesosoma is not elongate, and the pygidium is broadly ovate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFE2FFD06BC75B8AFAA0FE21" box="[192,1373,410,434]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFE2FFD06BC75B8AFAA0FE21" blockId="25.[192,1373,410,434]" box="[192,1373,410,434]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06BC75B8AFE65FE21" bold="true" box="[192,408,410,434]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Included taxon.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFE2FFD06A985B8AFC14FE21" authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[415,1001,410,434]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virginalis">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06A985B8AFD0FFE21" box="[415,754,410,434]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Traumatomutilla virginalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D47225BDFFE2FFD068055B8AFC1FFE21" author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[770,994,410,434]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFE2FFD06F205B8AFAA5FE21" authority="(Cresson, 1902)" baseAuthorityName="Cresson" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[1063,1368,410,434]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellica">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06F205B8AFB65FE21" box="[1063,1176,410,434]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">T. bellica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D47225BDFFE2FFD06FA05B8AFAADFE21" author="Cresson, E. T." box="[1191,1360,410,434]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 82" refId="ref18885" refString="Cresson, E. T. 1902. Descriptions of some Brazilian Mutilla. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 28: 1 - 82." type="journal article" year="1902">Cresson,1902</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFE2FFD06BC75BDAFE45FD91" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFE2FFD06BC75BDAFE45FD91" blockId="25.[192,1440,458,514]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06BC75BDAFE8EFE71" bold="true" box="[192,371,458,482]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Distribution.</emphasis>
Species of the bellica group have been found so far in Chaco areas of 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFE2FFD06FBE5BDAFAD2FE71" box="[1209,1327,458,482]" name="Paraguay" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and Cerrado areas of 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFE2FFD06A615BFAFE48FD91" box="[358,437,490,514]" name="Brazil" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFE2FFD06BC7580AFDE8FCE0" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFE2FFD06BC7580AFC23FD01" blockId="25.[192,1440,538,883]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06BC7580AFEBEFDA1" bold="true" box="[192,323,538,562]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Remarks.</emphasis>
The two species of this group can be differentiated most readily by coloration and distribution; 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFE2FFD06A07582BFE8EFDC1" baseAuthorityName="Cresson" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[256,371,570,594]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellica">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06A07582BFE8EFDC1" box="[256,371,570,594]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">T. bellica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the head and mesosomal dorsum setae entirely black (
<figureCitation id="28D844C9FFE2FFD06F52582AFB56FDC1" box="[1109,1195,570,594]" captionStart="Figures 51–55" captionStartId="27.[192,287,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[192,1438,280,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[192,1438,280,1801]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Figures 51–55. Traumatomutilla bellica (Cresson, 1902), ♀, holotype. 51) Dorsal habitus, line 3mm. 52) Lateral habitus, line 3mm. 53) Head, frontal view. 54) T6 (pygidium), posterior view. 55) Holotype labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674823" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674823/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
) and is known only from the Brazilian Cerrado, while 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFE2FFD06965584BFD05FDE1" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[610,760,602,626]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virginalis">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFE2FFD06965584BFD05FDE1" box="[610,760,602,626]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">T. virginalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has whitish setae on the propodeum and vertex dorsum (
<figureCitation id="28D844C9FFE2FFD06BCE586AFEE3FD01" box="[201,286,634,658]" captionStart="Figures 56–57" captionStartId="28.[192,287,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[277,1355,220,1844]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[277,1355,220,1844]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figures 56–57. Traumatomutilla virginalis (Gerstaecker, 1874), ♀, holotype, line 2mm. 56) Dorsal habitus. 57) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674825" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674825/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Fig. 56</figureCitation>
) and its distribution extends into the Paraguayan 
<collectingRegion id="722796AEFFE2FFD0688C586AFC27FD01" box="[907,986,634,658]" country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Chaco</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFE2FFD06BEF588BFDE8FCE0" blockId="25.[192,1440,538,883]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Apart from the characters mentioned in the species group diagnosis, both species from the bellica group have two apparently exclusive characters: the metafemur is strongly and subacutely projected posterodistally, in contrast to having a truncate metafemur and the intervals of the dorsal mesosomal sculpture form longitudinal sinuous carinae. Some species of the inermis group appear to approximate the first character whilst some species of the trochanterata group appear to approximate the latter. In both of these groups, however, the posterior margin of the head is armed with tubercles, which are lacking in the bellica group.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
